<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>The cash-flow projections have been derived from the following dtata:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">T. Martin Blaiklock</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> (HSR 019)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">HS2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">FOLLOW-UP</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ansport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Committee is to examine the Economic Assessment of the HS2 project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and, in particular, the KPMG Economic Assessment..</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I have been a consultant, banker and practitioner in infrastructure and energy project finance, - PFI, PPP and the like, - for the last </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">30 years or more, with both UK and wide overseas experience.  I have also given Seminars and Courses on this topic in more than 40 countries </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the last 5 years.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Comment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The Green Book:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Daily we are bombarded with figures as to why HS2 should rece</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ive the "go ahead".</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the methodology used to develop the figures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as presented in the KPMG Review, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is based upon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">procedures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> described in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HM Treasury’s Green Book</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Unfortunately, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there are two flaws in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> methodology that are never seemingly questioned:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1. the discount rate used to express future costs and revenues in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">today’s values; and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the use of the concept of “Optimism Bias”.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Discount Rate:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most people live in an "nominal' world, i.e. we take into account the impact of inflation on current and future costs and revenues in cash-flow projections, and include assumptions for the costs of finance and tax accordingly. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hence, in choosing a discoun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t rate to bring future values back to today, we choose our "cost of money", or thereabouts. Mathematically, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arriving at  Present Values </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it is compound interest, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which we all learn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in GCSE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at school, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">working backwards!</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently, the Government's "cost </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of money" [i.e. yield for 30 year Gilts] is around 3.7%, so arguably that is close to their "nominal" discount rate;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> / HM Treasury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, on the other hand, has, since the late 1980s, lived in a “real” world, i.e. they ignore, or exclude, infla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion and the costs of finance and tax from their investment assessments.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hence, if you assume that inflation is currently, say, 2.7%, taking that from the “nominal” discount rate (cost of money) of 3.7%, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">leaves you with a notional "real" discount rate for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Government of close to 1% p.a.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Notwithstanding the above, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">“real” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">discount rate used by Dept of Transport [DfT] and Government in their analyses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for HS2 was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.5%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, - as determined by HM Treasury's Green Book, published March 2003*.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">[Looking at it a different way, a “real” discount rate of 3.5% is equivalent today to around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">% “nominal” after adding inflation (2.7%), compared with the Government’s actual, i.e. “nominal”, cost of money = </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">3.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">%!].</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hence, the DfT et al., notwithstanding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that they calculate comparisons in “real” terms, have been using a discount rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">approx.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.5% highe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r than normal analysis would suggest is appropriate. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Taken over 30 years, this differential in discount rate represents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Present Value terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a multiple</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of around 110%!! </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is it not surprising that they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> et al.,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">get their sums and comparisons of alternatives wrong???</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, just as for the West-Coast Rail Franchise, DfT mixed in some ‘nominal” data into their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“real” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic calculatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns for HS2, e.g. tax revenues, VAT, GDP growth, etc., whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h arise after financing costs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">muddl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the calculations even more!!</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">[* = before 2003, a “real</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> discount rate of 6% p.a. was imposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> by Treasury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, which was equivalent to a rate of 8.5 - 9% “nominal”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> rate, when at th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> time the long-term cost of borrowing for Government was around 5.5-6%.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Is it not surprising, therefore, that for many PFI projects, - which push out into the future the payments Government has to make to finance the assets, like a cre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">dit card,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">- the projected Present Value costs for the PFI option were always going to look cheaper than conventional funding? Many PFI hospital projects suffered through such flawed decision-making.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The same prognosis can be applied to recent rail franchis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">es, e.g. West Coast Main</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Line.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">]</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Optimism Bias (“OB”)</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2003, Government introduced the empirical concept of “Optimism Bias”, a concept which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> again, I have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adopt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Based on a consultant’s report of a range of projects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undertaken in 1980- 1990’s, Government/HM Treasury derived multiples, which they would apply to cost estimates. Sometimes this multiple was applied to the estimates before making adjustments for risk, sometimes afterwards**</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">[**. there is a mathematical d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ifference. Network Rail and HM Treasury for a time applied OB both ways respectively, and both claimed they were right whichever way they used it!!!]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.06pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the case of the HS2 studies, the OB multiple used was 40-66%, i.e. up to two- thirds of the costs was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">added on to the DfT’s best estimates!! Such an assumption is completely unjustified and arbitrary. Notwithstanding the best intentions of those engineers providing their best-guess costs for HS2, the application of such OB multiples to the estimates does n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ot instill confidence in the projections at all!!</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAEsAAAABCAYAAACWjVPgAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAASSURBVChTY2BgYLAdxUSFgQ0AaI0R35kgxWcAAAAASUVORK5CYII=" width="75" height="1" alt="" /></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given the above, is it not time to question the use of the Green Book? I hope so, otherwise many more major UK infrastructure projects will be surrounded by controversy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Postscript:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Green Book Error:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">June 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HM Treasury published an update of the 2003 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">edition of the Green Book</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n Jan 27, 2003 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I alerted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HM Treasury </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(&amp; HM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Treasury ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">knowledged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there was an error</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or, possibly, just a misprint!, - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in one of the discount rates quoted in the Green Book. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">That error is still there today, 10 years on! </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I leave </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HM </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Treasury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> until 2023 to find it!! </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>